summary.seg: Cambridge, Corpus Christi College, MS 81 is a large decorated manuscript, written on paper, containing the works of Homer and Quintus of Smyrna, placed in consecutive order of the narrative. It was copied in the mid-fifteenth century by Demetrios Xanthopoulos, who worked in the circle of Cardinal Bessarion (1403-72). There are some scholia to Homer in the hand of Demetrios Chalkondyles, who supervised the production of the editio princeps of Homer in 1488.

The manuscript belonged to Theodore Gaza (ca. 1400-1475), and the cartouche on p. 1 could serve as a sign of ownership. His name may have led to the belief that the manuscript (along with MSS 224 and 248 at Corpus) came from Theodore of Tarsus (602-690). The manuscript was eventually bequeathed to Corpus Christi College by Matthew Parker.

support.material: pp. 1-1068 Western paper, folded in folio. Watermark: Letter T ( 75 40 ) middle of the folio comparable to Briquet 9129-9130 , dated 1441-1453.
pp. 1069-1070 Western paper, folded in folio. Watermark: crossbow ( 70 50 ) middle of the folio comparable to Briquet 760 , dated 1523.

foliation.p: ff. a-b + i-vii + pp. 1-986, 989-1070 + ff. viii-xv + c-d. Endleaves foliated in pencil in lower-case letters and Roman numerals in the upper right-hand corner, recto. The core of the manuscript is paginated in reddish pencil in Arabic numerals on rectos. Page number 679 is repeated twice, number 677 added in pencil. Page numbers 987-988 are missing.
An additional pagination in brown ink runs on the first 17 pages of the Odyssey, from p. 715 to p. 731.

p.fw: Running heads on rectos, with reference to the books of the Iliad

collation.p:
The manuscript consists of 53 quinions and a binion:
Quires 1-5310 pp. 1-1062
Quire 544 pp. 1063-1070
collation.signatures: Quire signatures in pencil in Arabic numerals on the lower outer corner of the first folio, recto from p. 21 (quire "2"). Quire number 17 is on p. 321 and repeated on p. 341. The following quire continues this mistake (18 on p. 361, etc.). Quire number 53 is on p. 1065.

supportDesc.condition: In fair condition. Traces of metal bosses from former binding visible on ff. i recto - iv recto and xiii recto - xv verso, some leaves that had been torn were repaired at the time of the binding with paper patches. On pp. 1041-1042 there is a round stain.

handNote.p: The manuscript was written by Demetrios Xanthopoulos Xanthopoulos, Demetrios (RGK I 98), active in the second half of 15th century.
The scholia are written by the byzantine scholar Demetrios Chalkondyles Calcondila, Demetrio, 1423-1511 (RGK I 105), active in the second half of 15th century.
Some notes are attributed to Theodorus Gaza Gazes, Theodoros, approximately 1400-approximately 1475 (RGK I 128), active between the first and the second half of 15th century.

decoDesc.decoNote: Major initial on p. 1 (Iliad, book 1) in gold surrounded by white branch-work on pink, blue and greenish grounds, in florentine style. Initials sketched in ink on pp. 19, 393, 408, 501, 524, 541, 601, 661, 715, 741, 755, 780, 804 (Iliad 2, 22, 23; Posthomerica 1, 3-5, 7, 12; Odyssey 1, 3-5, 7).

In the lower margin of p. 1 a green wreath with the name ΘΕΟΔΩΡΟΣ in gold capitals in it. On p. 1068 two miniatures inside medallions: a head with a turban in profile and an image of Athena with a spear; an analogous medallion with an image of Fortitude is drawn on Oxford, New College 233, f. 327v, which belonged to Demetrios Chalkondyles. A knot-work on p. 715 in reddish pencil.

additions.p: Four notes on f. i recto on Theodore of Tarsus (d. 690), archbishop of Canterbury, to whom the manuscript was believed to belong. The first note is by Matthew Parker Parker, Matthew, 1504-1575 , the second and the third by a second Western hand, the last one by a third hand.
p. 1 Matthaeus Cantuariensis added under the title.
Number of lines by a Western hand annotated next to last line of each page.

binding.p: Rebound by J.S. Wilson in October 1952: see note on f. a recto and stamp on right cover, inner.

history.origin: The manuscript was written in the mid-15th century by Demetrios Xanthopoulos.

provenance.p: The notes on f. i recto by Matthew Parker, his assistant John Joscelyn and his son John Parker suggest that the book was found at Canterbury, possibly as part of the library of St Augustine's Abbey. It was counted among the books believed to have belonged to Theodore of Tarsus (d. 690), archbishop of Canterbury. The manuscripts passed into Parker's collection.

history.acquisition:
The manuscript was bequeathed to Corpus Christi College by
Matthew Parker Parker, Matthew, 1504-1575 (b. 1504, d. 1575), the college's Master between 1544 and 1553, and Archbishop of Canterbury from 1559 until his death in 1575. It is listed in William Stanley's catalogue of 1722 at the classmark A.1.
